# Content Writing Guidelines

## Voice

Write as a surgeon explaining things to a patient in a consultation. Authoritative but warm. This is Matt's voice -- a foot and ankle surgeon who genuinely cares about the patient's recovery.

## Style Rules

**Plain language with medical terms explained inline:**
- "thrombosis (blocked vein)" not just "thrombosis"
- "ultrasound scan" not "sonographic imaging"

**Direct instructions, not hedged suggestions:**
- "You can (and should) walk" not "It may be beneficial to attempt ambulation"
- "It is important to NOT do vigorous stretches" not "Vigorous stretching is generally discouraged"

**Honest about uncertainty:**
- "No-one really knows the best duration to take blood-thinners for"
- Never invent false precision where evidence is unclear

**Concrete analogies:**
- "Your recovery is like the game Snakes and Ladders -- each week sees you closer to the finish. But one small mistake is like landing on the big snake that takes you right back to the beginning, with a re-rupture."

**Safety-first:**
- Every answer touching on risk must include warning signs and when to seek help
- "Swelling of the whole leg up to the knee should prompt medical review even if painless"

**Practical over theoretical:**
- Focus on what to do, not why it works biologically
- "If you remove the boot and stand up, the ankle will bend upwards and the repairing tendon is torn again" -- concrete consequence, not biology lecture

**Concise:**
- 1-3 paragraphs per FAQ answer
- No filler phrases: never use "This section covers...", "In this lesson you will learn...", "Let's explore..."
- No motivational padding in clinical content (keep hope anchors for mental health sections only)

**Product mentions -- natural, never pushy:**
- "The specially designed Achilles Rupture Splint from Thetis Medical solves these problems"
- Not "Buy our amazing splint!" or "Check out our product!"

**Cross-link instead of repeat:**
- "For a detailed week-by-week Achilles recovery timeline, see our dedicated guide" with link
- Never duplicate content that exists elsewhere; point to it

## i18n

All patient-facing content must be translated: en, de, fr, es, it. Use the same content object pattern as existing FAQ sections.

## Clinical Consistency

Always follow the positions in `.cursor/rules/achilles-clinical-positions.mdc`. If content would contradict a position, update the content, not the positions file (unless new evidence warrants a position change, which should be discussed first).

## Companion Commands

- `.cursor/commands/essentials-lesson.md`: Lesson structure template for course content (intro, action plan, key concept, normal vs urgent, tips, what's next)
- `.cursor/commands/surgeon-feedback-course-updates.md`: Process for applying surgeon/clinician feedback to existing lessons
